Verginius: in the year 69 Julius Vindex, legate of Gallia Lugdu· nensis, revolted against Nero and offered the throne to Galba the future emperor, then govemor of Hispania Tarraconensis3 Verginius Rufus, legate of Upper Germany, marched against Vindex and utterly defeated him3 though he fought for Nero then, he afterwards acquiesced in Nero's deposition, and hence is coupled here with Vindex and Galba. He refused the throne for himself on two different occasions, and died as a private citizen of the highest distinction Α. 1). 97. He was honoured with a public funeral, and a laudatio was pronounced over his remaius by Tacitus, consul in that year.
